WEBVTT

00:00:19.088 --> 00:00:20.630
YUFEI ZHAO: So the
first topic that I

00:00:20.630 --> 00:00:25.280
want to discuss in this course
is extremal graph theory.

00:00:38.980 --> 00:00:42.220
And in particular,
there is a whole class

00:00:42.220 --> 00:00:46.690
of problems which have to do
with what happens if you forbid

00:00:46.690 --> 00:00:47.750
a specific subgraph.

00:00:54.780 --> 00:00:56.400
Forbid a specific subgraph.

00:00:56.400 --> 00:00:59.400
And I ask you, what's the
maximum number of edges

00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:03.330
that can appear in your graph?

00:01:03.330 --> 00:01:05.129
In particular, and
this is the question

00:01:05.129 --> 00:01:08.700
that we saw at the
end of last lecture,

00:01:08.700 --> 00:01:12.070
which, now we're going to
pretend that's a theorem.

00:01:12.070 --> 00:01:18.510
Mantel's theorem
essentially asks,

00:01:18.510 --> 00:01:21.720
if you know that your graph
has no triangles, what's

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:25.770
the maximum number
of edges it can have?

00:01:25.770 --> 00:01:29.880
And Mantel's theorem tells
us that the extremal example

00:01:29.880 --> 00:01:35.940
is when your graph
consists of putting

00:01:35.940 --> 00:01:38.580
half the vertices
on one side, half

00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:41.220
the vertices on the
other side, and putting

00:01:41.220 --> 00:01:49.350
in all the edges
between the two sides.

00:01:49.350 --> 00:01:53.490
So this is a complete
bipartite graph.

00:01:53.490 --> 00:01:58.920
For these partitions, we denote
complete bipartite graphs

00:01:58.920 --> 00:02:00.980
like that.

00:02:00.980 --> 00:02:03.870
And Mantel's theorem
tells us that this graph,

00:02:03.870 --> 00:02:08.820
among triangle-free graphs,
has the most number of edges.

00:02:08.820 --> 00:02:21.740
Triangle-free graph, n
vertices, has at most--

00:02:21.740 --> 00:02:26.745
so the number of edges there
is n squared divided by 4.

00:02:26.745 --> 00:02:32.340
Round down-- that many edges.

00:02:32.340 --> 00:02:35.800
And from this example,
this bound is tight.

00:02:35.800 --> 00:02:37.260
So Mantel's theorem
them gives us

00:02:37.260 --> 00:02:40.620
a completely satisfactory
answer to the question of,

00:02:40.620 --> 00:02:42.630
what's the maximum
number of edges

00:02:42.630 --> 00:02:44.755
in a graph without triangles?

00:02:47.870 --> 00:02:51.500
And I want to begin by showing
you a few different proofs

00:02:51.500 --> 00:02:52.760
of Mantel's theorem.

00:02:52.760 --> 00:02:55.430
So we're illustrating
some different techniques

00:02:55.430 --> 00:02:57.870
in graph theory.

00:02:57.870 --> 00:03:00.890
So we'll see quite a few
proofs in today's lecture.

00:03:00.890 --> 00:03:04.010
The first one begins--

00:03:04.010 --> 00:03:05.990
well, here's the setup.

00:03:05.990 --> 00:03:09.660
I have G, an n vertex graph.

00:03:09.660 --> 00:03:17.190
And let me denote the vertices
and edges of G by V and E.

00:03:17.190 --> 00:03:23.040
If I have an edge in G
between vertices x and y,

00:03:23.040 --> 00:03:26.922
then note that they cannot
have any common neighbors.

00:03:35.300 --> 00:03:38.040
Because if they did, I
would see a triangle.

00:03:38.040 --> 00:03:40.039
So I assume G is triangle-free.

00:03:47.380 --> 00:03:51.190
So what can we say about
the degrees of the two

00:03:51.190 --> 00:03:53.830
endpoints of this edge?

00:03:53.830 --> 00:03:55.746
Well, they cannot add up to?

00:03:55.746 --> 00:03:57.783
AUDIENCE: They can't
have more than n.

00:03:57.783 --> 00:03:59.700
YUFEI ZHAO: They cannot
add up to more than n.

00:03:59.700 --> 00:04:02.750
So in particular-- so exactly.

00:04:02.750 --> 00:04:06.050
So the degrees of
these two endpoints,

00:04:06.050 --> 00:04:12.450
there's at most n
whenever xy is an edge.

00:04:12.450 --> 00:04:14.240
So here I'm using
d to denote degree.

00:04:19.450 --> 00:04:19.950
Well, OK.

00:04:19.950 --> 00:04:24.060
So now let me consider
the quantity which is

00:04:24.060 --> 00:04:25.995
the sum of the squared degrees.

00:04:30.140 --> 00:04:37.400
On one hand, I claim that the
sum is equal to this quantity

00:04:37.400 --> 00:04:40.280
here, where I sum
over all edges.

00:04:43.300 --> 00:04:45.580
And the reason is,
well, look at the sum.

00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:48.010
Suppose, imagine writing
out all the sum n's.

00:04:48.010 --> 00:04:51.632
How many times does
each dx come up?

00:04:51.632 --> 00:04:59.800
So each dx appears one
for each edge x is in,

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:01.820
so appears exactly dx times.

00:05:09.710 --> 00:05:14.120
But we saw from up here that
each sum n is at most n.

00:05:14.120 --> 00:05:18.710
So this sum here
is that most mn.

00:05:21.950 --> 00:05:25.010
On the other hand, let's
consider the quantity which

00:05:25.010 --> 00:05:26.465
is just the sum of the degrees.

00:05:29.690 --> 00:05:32.950
And you sometimes know it
as the handshaking lemma,

00:05:32.950 --> 00:05:37.210
that the sums of the degrees is
just twice the number of edges.

00:05:37.210 --> 00:05:40.840
Each edge is considered
twice in the sum.

00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:44.130
Well, now we apply the
Cauchy-Schwarz inequality,

00:05:44.130 --> 00:05:47.980
which, as you'll see many
times in this course,

00:05:47.980 --> 00:05:52.080
although you might think of it
as a fairly simple inequality,

00:05:52.080 --> 00:05:54.240
it's extremely powerful.

00:05:54.240 --> 00:05:57.925
And it will come up pretty
much throughout this course.

00:05:57.925 --> 00:05:59.300
By the Cauchy-Schwarz
inequality,

00:05:59.300 --> 00:06:01.020
you compare these
two quantities.

00:06:01.020 --> 00:06:15.130
I find that we have this
inequality over here relating

00:06:15.130 --> 00:06:18.490
the sums of the
degrees and square

00:06:18.490 --> 00:06:21.300
of the sum of the degrees.

00:06:21.300 --> 00:06:30.170
But we saw, on one hand, the
left-hand side is 4m squared.

00:06:30.170 --> 00:06:34.370
And we also saw that
the right-hand side

00:06:34.370 --> 00:06:39.870
is at most mn squared.

00:06:39.870 --> 00:06:44.850
Putting them together, we see
that m is at most n squared

00:06:44.850 --> 00:06:45.540
over 4.

00:06:45.540 --> 00:06:47.510
And of course, because
it's an integer,

00:06:47.510 --> 00:06:50.920
it's at most the
floor of this number.

00:06:50.920 --> 00:06:54.400
And that's a proof
of Mantel's theorem.

00:07:01.550 --> 00:07:05.090
What can you tell me about the
equality case in this proof?

00:07:11.660 --> 00:07:13.220
So I'll let you
think about that.

00:07:13.220 --> 00:07:14.930
But let me show you
some other proofs.

00:07:19.910 --> 00:07:22.970
In other words, are there
graphs with the same number

00:07:22.970 --> 00:07:25.820
of edges as the graph
shown up there that

00:07:25.820 --> 00:07:26.840
is also triangle-free?

00:07:26.840 --> 00:07:27.980
Is that a unique example?

00:07:31.465 --> 00:07:33.840
So let me show you a different
proof of Mantel's theorem.

00:07:38.400 --> 00:07:40.260
In this proof, so
we begin with a step

00:07:40.260 --> 00:07:43.090
that seems a little tricky.

00:07:43.090 --> 00:07:48.960
Let's let A be a
subset of vertices such

00:07:48.960 --> 00:08:01.426
that A is a largest
independent set of G.

00:08:01.426 --> 00:08:04.010
So remember, independent
set is a subset of vertices

00:08:04.010 --> 00:08:06.890
with no edges inside.

00:08:06.890 --> 00:08:09.770
It may have many
independent sets all having

00:08:09.770 --> 00:08:11.360
the same maximum size.

00:08:11.360 --> 00:08:14.120
Take one of them.

00:08:14.120 --> 00:08:15.930
So why should you do this step?

00:08:15.930 --> 00:08:17.650
Well, you know,
sometimes magic happens.

00:08:20.340 --> 00:08:25.280
Let's consider some vertex.

00:08:25.280 --> 00:08:28.440
So consider some
vertex, let's say x,

00:08:28.440 --> 00:08:32.809
and look at its neighborhood.

00:08:32.809 --> 00:08:36.400
The neighborhood must
be an independent set.

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:39.870
Otherwise, I get a triangle.

00:08:39.870 --> 00:08:46.780
So every neighborhood
is an independent set.

00:08:49.910 --> 00:08:53.740
And as a result, the
degree of every vertex

00:08:53.740 --> 00:08:58.010
is at most the size of the
largest independent set.

00:09:03.290 --> 00:09:23.950
So now, let B be the complement
of A. So I have this A and B.

00:09:23.950 --> 00:09:28.180
Every edge has to intersect
B. The edge cannot be entirely

00:09:28.180 --> 00:09:30.010
containing A, because
it has no edges.

00:09:39.870 --> 00:09:48.090
So the number of edges
of G is at most--

00:09:48.090 --> 00:09:55.140
well, I count over the
vertices in B, the degree.

00:09:55.140 --> 00:09:56.690
So maybe I overcount.

00:09:56.690 --> 00:10:00.020
So the edges containing B, I
count twice, but that's OK.

00:10:00.020 --> 00:10:03.550
So this is an upper bound
on the number of edges.

00:10:03.550 --> 00:10:06.920
But I also know that
every vertex in the graph

00:10:06.920 --> 00:10:10.490
has a degree at
most the size of A.

00:10:10.490 --> 00:10:15.270
So each sum n is at most the
size of A. And I have B terms.

00:10:17.810 --> 00:10:19.440
So I have that.

00:10:19.440 --> 00:10:31.240
Now, by the AMGM inequality,
you'll have that.

00:10:31.240 --> 00:10:36.410
And the sizes of A and B
add up to the entire vertex

00:10:36.410 --> 00:10:42.322
set, n squared over 4.

00:10:42.322 --> 00:10:46.180
So that gives you another
proof of Mantel's theorem.

00:10:48.910 --> 00:10:51.940
What does this proof tell
us about the equality case?

00:10:55.876 --> 00:10:58.710
Now, something I always want
you to keep in mind when

00:10:58.710 --> 00:11:00.870
we do proofs is,
especially if we

00:11:00.870 --> 00:11:03.660
have a tight example like that--
and later on in the course,

00:11:03.660 --> 00:11:05.970
we'll almost never have
good examples like that.

00:11:05.970 --> 00:11:08.100
So this is still early
on in the course.

00:11:08.100 --> 00:11:10.530
And we're still very clean
in the examples-- is to keep

00:11:10.530 --> 00:11:12.960
the extremal example in mind.

00:11:12.960 --> 00:11:16.140
And every step in
your proof, it should

00:11:16.140 --> 00:11:18.180
be tight for that example.

00:11:18.180 --> 00:11:21.050
Otherwise, something went
wrong with your proof.

00:11:21.050 --> 00:11:23.860
Let's think about
the inequalities.

00:11:23.860 --> 00:11:33.690
At equality, we must have that--

00:11:33.690 --> 00:11:38.430
so looking at this inequality.

00:11:38.430 --> 00:11:49.595
So there are no edges in
B. We also have that--

00:11:52.385 --> 00:12:07.290
so by that, so every vertex in
B is complete to A. And finally,

00:12:07.290 --> 00:12:09.180
A and B should
have the same size.

00:12:12.880 --> 00:12:15.270
So it is exactly the
configuration shown up there.

00:12:15.270 --> 00:12:18.790
Now, when n is odd,
we're rounding down by 1.

00:12:18.790 --> 00:12:20.580
So you can lose a little bit.

00:12:20.580 --> 00:12:22.870
But you can check
that actually what

00:12:22.870 --> 00:12:25.420
we described up there is
also the unique example.

00:12:29.080 --> 00:12:31.380
So that graph, the
complete bipartite graph

00:12:31.380 --> 00:12:35.530
with two equal parts, is
the unique maximal example,

00:12:35.530 --> 00:12:37.770
number of edges in a
triangle-free graph.

00:12:42.216 --> 00:12:43.210
Great.

00:12:43.210 --> 00:12:45.970
So once we know
what the answer is

00:12:45.970 --> 00:12:49.240
for triangle-free, of course,
we should ask further questions.

00:12:49.240 --> 00:12:50.950
Instead of forbidding
a triangle,

00:12:50.950 --> 00:12:53.520
what if we forbid other graphs?

00:12:53.520 --> 00:12:57.570
And what are some natural
next steps to take?

00:12:57.570 --> 00:13:01.690
Well, say, instead of triangles,
we can ask, what about if we

00:13:01.690 --> 00:13:06.550
forbid a K4, a clique
of four vertices?

00:13:06.550 --> 00:13:10.240
Or in general, what if we
forbid a clique on the fixed

00:13:10.240 --> 00:13:11.170
number of vertices?

00:13:11.170 --> 00:13:20.450
So what is the maximum number
of edges in a Kr plus 1-free--

00:13:20.450 --> 00:13:24.080
there's a good reason
why index is r plus 1--

00:13:24.080 --> 00:13:28.670
graph on n vertices.

00:13:28.670 --> 00:13:31.850
So for example, if we're
interested in K4-free--

00:13:38.400 --> 00:13:40.830
so what might be a good
candidate for a graph with lots

00:13:40.830 --> 00:13:42.790
of edges that has no K4's?

00:13:42.790 --> 00:13:44.610
I mean, certainly,
that example we saw,

00:13:44.610 --> 00:13:47.540
it does not have K4's, because
it doesn't have any triangles.

00:13:47.540 --> 00:13:50.820
But we can do even better.

00:13:50.820 --> 00:13:55.860
Instead of taking two parts,
you can take more parts.

00:13:55.860 --> 00:14:00.450
For K4, if I take
three parts, each

00:14:00.450 --> 00:14:03.910
with n/3 number of
vertices, of course,

00:14:03.910 --> 00:14:07.020
if n is not divisible by
3, round up and run down.

00:14:07.020 --> 00:14:13.680
And putting all the edges
between different parts,

00:14:13.680 --> 00:14:15.900
you can see this
graph here has no K4.

00:14:18.880 --> 00:14:22.210
So that's an example
of a K4-free graph.

00:14:22.210 --> 00:14:25.670
Well, does it have the maximum
possible number of edges?

00:14:25.670 --> 00:14:28.270
So is this the best
that we can do?

00:14:28.270 --> 00:14:30.220
So it turns out
the answer is yes.

00:14:30.220 --> 00:14:32.820
And that's the next
theorem that we'll see.

00:14:32.820 --> 00:14:36.130
But just to give it a name, so
we're going to call graphs like

00:14:36.130 --> 00:14:38.010
these Turán graphs.

00:14:38.010 --> 00:14:40.735
So the next theorem
is proved by Turán.

00:14:40.735 --> 00:14:42.100
It's Turán's theorem.

00:14:42.100 --> 00:14:48.940
So a Turán graph, so
we'll denote T sub nr.

00:14:48.940 --> 00:14:59.450
It is a complete
r-partite graph such

00:14:59.450 --> 00:15:06.250
that there are n
vertices whose part sizes

00:15:06.250 --> 00:15:12.289
are all nearly the same,
up to at most 1 difference.

00:15:18.160 --> 00:15:19.930
So this is an example here.

00:15:19.930 --> 00:15:25.770
But in general, maybe
you have r parts.

00:15:28.460 --> 00:15:38.780
And I put in all the edges
between different parts.

00:15:43.720 --> 00:15:45.940
So it's not too hard to
calculate the number of edges

00:15:45.940 --> 00:15:47.470
in such a graph.

00:15:47.470 --> 00:15:50.470
And Turán's theorem tells
us that that is the extremal

00:15:50.470 --> 00:15:51.620
example.

00:15:51.620 --> 00:15:55.720
You cannot do better in
terms of getting more edges.

00:16:05.510 --> 00:16:15.950
So if G is an n vertex, try
a K sub r plus 1-free graph.

00:16:18.610 --> 00:16:28.170
Then it has at most the number
of edges of the Turán graph.

00:16:36.020 --> 00:16:38.360
It's a generalization
of Mantel's theorem.

00:16:38.360 --> 00:16:42.350
And well, you can think about
if the proofs that we did

00:16:42.350 --> 00:16:46.310
for Mantel's generalizes
to Turán's theorem.

00:16:46.310 --> 00:16:50.360
And it's actually not
entirely clear how to do it.

00:16:50.360 --> 00:16:53.390
So let me present for you
three different proofs

00:16:53.390 --> 00:16:55.598
of Turán's theorem.

00:16:55.598 --> 00:16:57.140
So some of them,
you can think about,

00:16:57.140 --> 00:16:59.240
are they related to the
proofs of Mantel's theorem

00:16:59.240 --> 00:16:59.740
that we did?

00:16:59.740 --> 00:17:02.930
And they all are going to look
somewhat different, but maybe

00:17:02.930 --> 00:17:06.280
superficially.

00:17:06.280 --> 00:17:13.930
The first proof, we
will use induction

00:17:13.930 --> 00:17:15.299
on the number of vertices.

00:17:18.250 --> 00:17:21.089
So actually, this is one of the
very few times in this course

00:17:21.089 --> 00:17:23.212
where we will see induction.

00:17:23.212 --> 00:17:25.170
So of course, induction
is a powerful technique

00:17:25.170 --> 00:17:25.920
in combinatorics.

00:17:25.920 --> 00:17:28.000
But for almost the
rest of the course,

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:30.030
we're not going to
have clean examples.

00:17:30.030 --> 00:17:32.280
And when we do have clean
examples to work with,

00:17:32.280 --> 00:17:36.640
somehow increasing n by 1
doesn't buy you all that much.

00:17:36.640 --> 00:17:40.020
Here, there are very clean
examples, very clean answers,

00:17:40.020 --> 00:17:42.360
and induction works
out quite well.

00:17:45.640 --> 00:17:48.130
When n is small, of course,
you should always address that.

00:17:48.130 --> 00:17:49.600
You can come up with
many funny proofs

00:17:49.600 --> 00:17:51.142
if you don't address
when n is small.

00:17:51.142 --> 00:17:55.840
So when n is small, this
problem is basically trivial.

00:17:55.840 --> 00:17:57.310
n is almost r.

00:17:57.310 --> 00:18:01.210
You could have the complete
graph on r vertices.

00:18:01.210 --> 00:18:03.350
And then we're good.

00:18:03.350 --> 00:18:10.090
So let's assume that
we're not in this case.

00:18:10.090 --> 00:18:11.810
And also, by
induction hypothesis,

00:18:11.810 --> 00:18:19.345
let's assume that it is true
for all graphs fewer than n

00:18:19.345 --> 00:18:19.845
vertices.

00:18:24.480 --> 00:18:31.830
And let G be a graph
that is K sub r

00:18:31.830 --> 00:18:36.990
plus 1-free on n vertices.

00:18:36.990 --> 00:18:41.800
And also, let's assume a
maximum example to begin with.

00:18:41.800 --> 00:18:44.610
So let's assume that
the G that you chose

00:18:44.610 --> 00:18:50.350
has already the maximum
possible number of edges.

00:18:50.350 --> 00:18:52.310
There are only finite
of any such examples.

00:18:52.310 --> 00:18:55.230
So pick one that already has
the maximum number of edges.

00:18:55.230 --> 00:18:59.190
And let's think about what
properties this graph G has.

00:18:59.190 --> 00:19:08.460
I claim that G must already
contain a clique on r vertices.

00:19:13.230 --> 00:19:14.390
So think about that.

00:19:14.390 --> 00:19:18.290
If G does not contain
a clique on r vertices,

00:19:18.290 --> 00:19:20.240
then I can add in more edges.

00:19:28.600 --> 00:19:34.100
And I can still
maintain the property

00:19:34.100 --> 00:19:35.960
of being K sub r plus 1-free.

00:19:40.480 --> 00:19:44.320
So I can assume that G
must contain a K sub r.

00:19:44.320 --> 00:19:48.320
So let's look at one
of these K sub r's.

00:19:48.320 --> 00:20:04.200
So let n be the vertices
of some r clique in G.

00:20:04.200 --> 00:20:12.420
So we have some A. And
the complement to that,

00:20:12.420 --> 00:20:21.490
let me call that B.

00:20:21.490 --> 00:20:28.940
Look at the vertex in B. How
many neighbors can have in A?

00:20:28.940 --> 00:20:32.730
It cannot be complete to A,
otherwise I would have an r

00:20:32.730 --> 00:20:34.610
plus 1 clique.

00:20:34.610 --> 00:20:51.200
So every vertex in B has at
most r minus 1 neighbors in A.

00:20:51.200 --> 00:20:53.700
So let's count all the edges.

00:20:56.640 --> 00:21:00.530
The number of edges
in G is that most--

00:21:00.530 --> 00:21:04.070
well, first, we should account
for the edges inside A.

00:21:04.070 --> 00:21:08.730
And there are-- or
choose two of them.

00:21:08.730 --> 00:21:13.080
And then the edges between
A and B, for every vertex

00:21:13.080 --> 00:21:19.050
in B, there are at most
r minus 1 vertices going

00:21:19.050 --> 00:21:32.650
to A for each vertex in B. And
finally, the edge set of B.

00:21:32.650 --> 00:21:38.060
Well, we can say something
more about these quantities.

00:21:38.060 --> 00:21:42.740
We know that the size of
B is exactly n minus r.

00:21:45.560 --> 00:21:49.060
But what can we say about
the number of edges in B?

00:21:49.060 --> 00:21:51.450
We can use induction hypothesis.

00:21:51.450 --> 00:21:55.990
So B is also r
plus 1 clique-free.

00:21:55.990 --> 00:21:59.080
So the number of edges is
at most the number of edges

00:21:59.080 --> 00:22:02.920
in a corresponding Turán graph.

00:22:02.920 --> 00:22:05.880
Now, at this point, you
can do a calculation.

00:22:05.880 --> 00:22:08.100
Well, I mean, you should
expect that the answer

00:22:08.100 --> 00:22:10.680
we're looking for is--

00:22:10.680 --> 00:22:13.350
I mean, this should be
equal to the number of edges

00:22:13.350 --> 00:22:14.430
in the Turán graph.

00:22:14.430 --> 00:22:16.410
So you can either
do a calculation

00:22:16.410 --> 00:22:18.630
to figure this out,
or remember what

00:22:18.630 --> 00:22:23.400
I said earlier, that keep
the tight example in mind,

00:22:23.400 --> 00:22:26.640
and everything should check
out for the tight example.

00:22:26.640 --> 00:22:30.570
So in particular, if
you are in the situation

00:22:30.570 --> 00:22:37.750
of a complete multipartite
graph with equal size or nearly

00:22:37.750 --> 00:22:42.540
equal-size parts, what is A?

00:22:49.780 --> 00:22:52.740
So A is one vertex
from each part.

00:22:56.270 --> 00:22:58.560
So you take out one
vertex from each part.

00:23:02.960 --> 00:23:07.610
And read off this calculation
for this graph over here.

00:23:07.610 --> 00:23:10.042
And then you see that
that is indeed equality.

00:23:10.042 --> 00:23:11.000
So it should check out.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:13.824
You don't need to do
any actual calculations.

00:23:19.150 --> 00:23:21.890
Any questions about the
proofs we've done so far?

00:23:25.285 --> 00:23:28.200
All right.

00:23:28.200 --> 00:23:31.140
Let me show you another
proof of Turán's theorem.

00:23:39.390 --> 00:23:43.970
So this proof has a name.

00:23:43.970 --> 00:23:46.552
So it's called Zykov's
symmetrization.

00:23:55.408 --> 00:23:58.020
So Zykov has the
unfortunate honor

00:23:58.020 --> 00:24:00.120
of having a name
that's hard to beat

00:24:00.120 --> 00:24:02.320
in terms of alphabetical order.

00:24:02.320 --> 00:24:04.180
I think, if he and I
were to write a paper,

00:24:04.180 --> 00:24:05.430
I wouldn't be the last author.

00:24:09.730 --> 00:24:12.550
So what's this about?

00:24:12.550 --> 00:24:16.930
So let G be the graph.

00:24:16.930 --> 00:24:20.690
Again, as before, we're going
to take a maximal example.

00:24:20.690 --> 00:24:30.810
So be the n-vertex graph
that is free of cliques

00:24:30.810 --> 00:24:35.790
of r plus 1 vertices and has
already the maximum number

00:24:35.790 --> 00:24:36.400
of edges.

00:24:44.410 --> 00:24:46.850
So here's the property I want
to prove about this graph.

00:24:50.090 --> 00:24:55.240
I claim that if you look at
the complement of the graph,

00:24:55.240 --> 00:24:57.980
of this extremal
example, it must

00:24:57.980 --> 00:25:00.230
be an equivalence relation.

00:25:00.230 --> 00:25:07.970
So more precisely, claim
that if xy is a non-edge,

00:25:07.970 --> 00:25:19.650
and yz is a non-edge, then
xz must also be a non-edge.

00:25:19.650 --> 00:25:27.270
So in other words, non-edges
form equivalence relation.

00:25:34.973 --> 00:25:36.390
And again, you
should always think

00:25:36.390 --> 00:25:39.390
about the extremal example.

00:25:39.390 --> 00:25:41.330
And it is true for
the extremal example.

00:25:41.330 --> 00:25:44.005
Because the complement
are a bunch of cliques.

00:25:44.005 --> 00:25:45.380
So it is an
equivalence relation.

00:25:51.830 --> 00:25:53.310
So let's prove this claim.

00:25:53.310 --> 00:25:57.240
So let's assume that the
conclusion is not true.

00:25:57.240 --> 00:26:06.240
So suppose, for the contrary,
that we have xy and yz being

00:26:06.240 --> 00:26:12.000
non-edges, but xz is an edge.

00:26:24.480 --> 00:26:26.580
So let's think
about what happens

00:26:26.580 --> 00:26:32.210
to the degrees of
non-adjacent vertices.

00:26:32.210 --> 00:26:36.710
So I claim that
if the degree of y

00:26:36.710 --> 00:26:40.920
were smaller than
the degree of x, then

00:26:40.920 --> 00:26:42.880
I can do something
to the graph that

00:26:42.880 --> 00:26:47.150
violates the maximality
of the number of edges.

00:26:47.150 --> 00:26:59.250
Namely, I can replace
y by a clone of x.

00:27:01.840 --> 00:27:05.230
So I chop off y from the graph.

00:27:05.230 --> 00:27:06.550
And I look at x.

00:27:06.550 --> 00:27:07.990
And I clone.

00:27:07.990 --> 00:27:12.100
So cloning it means
taking some x prime.

00:27:12.100 --> 00:27:17.500
And I join x prime to all
the same neighbors as x.

00:27:17.500 --> 00:27:21.790
So clone x into some
other vertex, x prime.

00:27:21.790 --> 00:27:24.430
Now, when you do this,
I claim that you also

00:27:24.430 --> 00:27:30.820
get a graph that is
free of K sub r plus 1.

00:27:34.740 --> 00:27:41.630
So we also obtain a K
sub r plus 1-free graph.

00:27:45.230 --> 00:27:46.325
So why is that?

00:27:46.325 --> 00:27:50.710
So if you were to have
an r plus 1 clique,

00:27:50.710 --> 00:27:54.510
well, it shouldn't have
both x and x clone.

00:27:54.510 --> 00:27:56.410
Because there's no
edge between them.

00:27:56.410 --> 00:27:59.468
So it only has one
of x and x clone.

00:27:59.468 --> 00:28:02.010
But then that would have been
a clique in the original graph.

00:28:07.300 --> 00:28:12.460
However, what about
the number of edges

00:28:12.460 --> 00:28:16.300
that we obtain after
this transformation?

00:28:16.300 --> 00:28:20.800
If x had more outgoing
edges, a higher degree

00:28:20.800 --> 00:28:24.790
than y, then cloning
x to replace y

00:28:24.790 --> 00:28:26.500
increases the number of edges.

00:28:31.840 --> 00:28:35.780
We obtain a graph that is
also K sub r plus 1-free

00:28:35.780 --> 00:28:45.820
and has more edges than
G, which is not possible,

00:28:45.820 --> 00:28:49.180
because we assumed that g
started with the maximum number

00:28:49.180 --> 00:28:51.163
of edges.

00:28:51.163 --> 00:29:00.600
So therefore, the degree of y is
at most the degree x, basically

00:29:00.600 --> 00:29:05.520
for every non-edge xy.

00:29:08.780 --> 00:29:12.080
Likewise, we also
have that there

00:29:12.080 --> 00:29:13.840
is no edge between y and z.

00:29:17.610 --> 00:29:20.400
So the degree of y is--

00:29:23.712 --> 00:29:25.920
thus the degree of y is at
least the degree of x now.

00:29:25.920 --> 00:29:30.748
So degree of y is at
least the degree of z.

00:29:33.700 --> 00:29:38.910
Now, y has a lot
of outgoing edges.

00:29:38.910 --> 00:29:44.160
So now let's replace both
x and z by clones of y.

00:29:56.760 --> 00:30:02.650
As before, we obtain some
graph that we'll call G prime.

00:30:02.650 --> 00:30:07.600
And G prime, same reason as
before, is K sub r plus 1-free.

00:30:07.600 --> 00:30:12.100
If you had a K sub r plus
1, then the same clique

00:30:12.100 --> 00:30:16.390
should have shown up in
G. So G prime does not

00:30:16.390 --> 00:30:18.130
have r plus 1 cliques either.

00:30:18.130 --> 00:30:20.960
But what about the number
of edges in G prime?

00:30:25.460 --> 00:30:27.490
So the number of
edges in G prime--

00:30:27.490 --> 00:30:34.320
well, we started with
G. We deleted x and z.

00:30:34.320 --> 00:30:42.170
So we deleted this many edges.

00:30:42.170 --> 00:30:43.730
Here, we're crucially
using the fact

00:30:43.730 --> 00:30:47.260
that there is an
edge between x and z.

00:30:47.260 --> 00:30:51.160
But now we also added
back in a bunch of edges

00:30:51.160 --> 00:30:53.320
coming from the clone of y.

00:30:53.320 --> 00:30:59.482
And they are 2 times
dy edges added back in.

00:30:59.482 --> 00:31:02.240
Now, you see, because y
has degree at least that

00:31:02.240 --> 00:31:06.680
of both x and z, we obtain
that this number of edges

00:31:06.680 --> 00:31:13.010
is strictly bigger than
that of G, which contradicts

00:31:13.010 --> 00:31:29.080
the maximality of G.

00:31:29.080 --> 00:31:32.410
So at this point, we know
that the complement of G

00:31:32.410 --> 00:31:35.390
must be an equivalence relation.

00:31:35.390 --> 00:31:38.910
So the complement is
a bunch of cliques.

00:31:38.910 --> 00:31:40.613
And that's a lot of information.

00:31:40.613 --> 00:31:42.030
So that's almost
the best thing we

00:31:42.030 --> 00:31:43.822
can hope for is the
structural information.

00:31:43.822 --> 00:31:46.510
We're not quite done yet.

00:31:46.510 --> 00:31:47.220
And why is that?

00:31:50.860 --> 00:31:52.962
Well, we're almost there.

00:31:52.962 --> 00:31:54.170
But we're not quite done yet.

00:31:57.128 --> 00:32:00.086
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
you can figure out

00:32:00.086 --> 00:32:02.155
the sizes [INAUDIBLE].

00:32:02.155 --> 00:32:02.780
YUFEI ZHAO: OK.

00:32:02.780 --> 00:32:08.590
So we need to figure out the
sizes of the individual parts.

00:32:08.590 --> 00:32:11.390
So we need to figure out the
sizes of individual parts.

00:32:11.390 --> 00:32:15.610
And also, note that you
cannot have too many parts.

00:32:15.610 --> 00:32:20.950
So at this point,
after the claim,

00:32:20.950 --> 00:32:28.210
we know that G is a
complete multipartite graph.

00:32:38.810 --> 00:32:43.130
It has at most r parts.

00:32:43.130 --> 00:32:45.710
If it had r plus 1 parts,
I would see a clique

00:32:45.710 --> 00:32:46.745
in r plus 1 vertices.

00:32:51.080 --> 00:32:53.665
So then, finally,
I need to show--

00:32:53.665 --> 00:32:55.390
I mean, the rest
is fairly routine.

00:32:55.390 --> 00:32:58.540
I need to show what
the part sizes have

00:32:58.540 --> 00:33:01.180
to be to maximize
the number of edges.

00:33:01.180 --> 00:33:03.535
And basically, if you
had some two parts--

00:33:06.660 --> 00:33:08.690
so consider exactly r parts.

00:33:08.690 --> 00:33:10.090
They're all empty parts.

00:33:10.090 --> 00:33:12.780
And some two parts
have the number

00:33:12.780 --> 00:33:23.390
of vertices differing
by more than 1.

00:33:23.390 --> 00:33:27.350
Then what I can do is--

00:33:27.350 --> 00:33:32.956
so if you had one part much
bigger than the other part,

00:33:32.956 --> 00:33:36.730
you can imagine moving
one vertex from one part

00:33:36.730 --> 00:33:38.690
to the other part.

00:33:38.690 --> 00:33:41.540
And you should convince yourself
that this operation should

00:33:41.540 --> 00:33:44.270
strictly increase
the number of edges.

00:33:50.520 --> 00:34:01.700
And then moving vertices
should strictly increase

00:34:01.700 --> 00:34:04.960
the number of edges of G.

00:34:04.960 --> 00:34:06.720
And putting this
all together, we

00:34:06.720 --> 00:34:09.840
see that the extremal
example necessarily

00:34:09.840 --> 00:34:14.070
has to be the
current graph, namely

00:34:14.070 --> 00:34:19.630
a complete r-partite
graph, where

00:34:19.630 --> 00:34:22.860
all the parts have
the same size, up

00:34:22.860 --> 00:34:24.456
to almost 1 difference.

00:34:29.126 --> 00:34:30.540
Great.

00:34:30.540 --> 00:34:33.030
Any questions?

00:34:33.030 --> 00:34:33.530
Yep?

00:34:33.530 --> 00:34:35.530
