00:34:52.719 --> 00:34:54.098
Any more questions?

00:34:58.082 --> 00:34:59.078
Great.

00:34:59.078 --> 00:35:03.180
And you see that in both proofs,
if you look at this proof

00:35:03.180 --> 00:35:05.100
as well, you see
that the Turán graph,

00:35:05.100 --> 00:35:09.370
it's the unique extremizer.

00:35:09.370 --> 00:35:12.250
I want to give you a
third proof that has

00:35:12.250 --> 00:35:13.730
a somewhat different flavor.

00:35:13.730 --> 00:35:16.000
So these two proofs,
they're both somewhat

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:17.265
combinatorial in flavor.

00:35:17.265 --> 00:35:22.340
So I'm doing some arguments
either looking at,

00:35:22.340 --> 00:35:24.730
in this case, a
clique and arguing

00:35:24.730 --> 00:35:26.050
what happens outside of it.

00:35:26.050 --> 00:35:29.230
And over there, again, I'm
looking at maximal example.

00:35:29.230 --> 00:35:30.910
The third proof
I want to show is

00:35:30.910 --> 00:35:32.770
more of a probabilistic proof.

00:35:32.770 --> 00:35:35.485
So this highlights an important
method in combinatorics,

00:35:35.485 --> 00:35:39.280
and almost a
probabilistic method,

00:35:39.280 --> 00:35:43.550
where we start with a problem
that comes with no randomness.

00:35:43.550 --> 00:35:48.920
But we introduce some randomness
to make the problem amenable.

00:35:48.920 --> 00:35:50.120
It's a very pretty idea.

00:36:02.480 --> 00:36:11.240
So we start, again, with G being
a n-uniform, so n-vertex, K sub

00:36:11.240 --> 00:36:17.520
r plus 1-free graph on m edges.

00:36:20.532 --> 00:36:25.700
And what I want to do is to
randomly sort the vertex set.

00:36:25.700 --> 00:36:36.400
Consider a random
order of the vertices.

00:36:42.620 --> 00:36:45.030
So I put all the
vertices on the line,

00:36:45.030 --> 00:36:47.610
but the vertices are
chosen at random order.

00:36:47.610 --> 00:36:53.574
And you see some of
the edges like that.

00:37:00.400 --> 00:37:03.070
Let me show you how
to find a clique.

00:37:03.070 --> 00:37:07.810
And essentially, we do
it in a not-so-smart way.

00:37:07.810 --> 00:37:11.620
Namely, I basically
pick all the vertices

00:37:11.620 --> 00:37:13.870
in some greedy-like
manner, where

00:37:13.870 --> 00:37:16.540
I include the vertex
in my set if it

00:37:16.540 --> 00:37:23.720
is adjacent to all
earlier vertices.

00:37:23.720 --> 00:37:28.730
So if all of its neighbors--

00:37:28.730 --> 00:37:35.090
so I include V, if
V is the earliest

00:37:35.090 --> 00:37:38.138
vertex among its neighbors.

00:37:45.800 --> 00:37:49.590
So earliest means the leftmost,
so if I go from left to right.

00:37:49.590 --> 00:37:54.680
So in this case up here, so
I look at the first vertex.

00:37:54.680 --> 00:37:58.335
Well, the first vertex
should always be in your set.

00:37:58.335 --> 00:38:01.440
So this vertex has one
neighbor, just to the right.

00:38:01.440 --> 00:38:04.600
So that's OK.

00:38:04.600 --> 00:38:09.350
And hold on.

00:38:09.350 --> 00:38:11.930
It's-- no.

00:38:11.930 --> 00:38:12.640
Sorry.

