equal to each
other, and you make

00:43:36.910 --> 00:43:39.250
them as close to each
other as possible.

00:43:41.840 --> 00:43:45.430
So with a little bit more work,
you can get the exact version

00:43:45.430 --> 00:43:46.740
of Turán's theorem up there.

00:43:46.740 --> 00:43:50.160
But at least what
we've shown is--

00:43:50.160 --> 00:43:58.000
so from here, we've shown that
the number of edges is at most

00:43:58.000 --> 00:43:59.950
this quantity, which,
for most purposes,

00:43:59.950 --> 00:44:01.997
is basically as good
as Turán's theorem.

00:44:06.650 --> 00:44:08.470
Any questions about
this proof here?

00:44:08.470 --> 00:44:11.046
And so it's a probabilistic
method of proof.

00:44:11.046 --> 00:44:13.600
So we're introducing
some randomness

00:44:13.600 --> 00:44:16.298
into the problem that
originally had no randomness.

00:44:19.510 --> 00:44:20.010
Great.

00:44:20.010 --> 00:44:22.500
So let's take a very
quick 2-minute break.

00:44:22.500 --> 00:44:26.150
And then when we come back,
I want to show you that even

00:44:26.150 --> 00:44:27.977
though we've shown so
many different proofs

00:44:27.977 --> 00:44:30.560
of Turán's theorem and Mantel's
theorem-- you might think, OK,

00:44:30.560 --> 00:44:32.900
this is a pretty simple thing--

00:44:32.900 --> 00:44:36.075
even if I tweak the
problem just a little bit,

00:44:36.075 --> 00:44:38.200
there are so many things
that we do not understand,

00:44:38.200 --> 00:44:41.460
and many important open problems
in combinatorics that are

00:44:41.460 --> 00:44:44.743
variants of Turán's theorem.

00:44:44.743 --> 00:44:45.910
So let's take a quick break.

00:44:51.960 --> 00:44:55.930
So so far we've been talking
about Turán's theorem,

00:44:55.930 --> 00:44:59.830
or generally the problem of, if
you forbid a certain structure,

00:44:59.830 --> 00:45:05.730
forbid a certain subgraph, what
is the maximum number of edges?

00:45:05.730 --> 00:45:07.970
We're going to spend the
next few lectures discussing

00:45:07.970 --> 00:45:09.480
more problems of that form.

00:45:09.480 --> 00:45:13.520
And it turns out, for the
answers we've just seen,

00:45:13.520 --> 00:45:15.300
they are deceptively simple.

00:45:15.300 --> 00:45:17.690
And for almost any
other situation,

00:45:17.690 --> 00:45:20.340
we don't really know
the exact answer.

00:45:20.340 --> 00:45:22.910
And for many questions, we
don't know anything close

00:45:22.910 --> 00:45:24.038
to the truth.

00:45:24.038 --> 00:45:25.580
And in particular,
I want to show you

00:45:25.580 --> 00:45:29.000
one variant of this
problem, namely

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:31.640
what happens, instead
of looking at graphs,

00:45:31.640 --> 00:45:33.640
if you look at hypergraphs.

00:45:33.640 --> 00:45:36.860
And there, that's a major
open problem in combinatorics,

00:45:36.860 --> 00:45:39.150
what the truth should be.

00:45:39.150 --> 00:45:47.850
So here is an open
problem, which is,

00:45:47.850 --> 00:45:53.270
what happens to Turán's theorem
for 3-uniform hypergraphs?

00:45:59.990 --> 00:46:02.570
So don't be scared by
the word hypergraph.

00:46:02.570 --> 00:46:06.160
So whereas you think of graphs
as having edges consisting

00:46:06.160 --> 00:46:08.260
of pairs of vertices,
a hypergraph

00:46:08.260 --> 00:46:12.200
is simply a structure where,
for a 3-uniform hypergraph,

00:46:12.200 --> 00:46:14.625
the edges are triples,
triples of vertices.

00:46:17.130 --> 00:46:26.770
So the question is, what is
the maximum number of triples

00:46:26.770 --> 00:46:37.820
in 3-uniform
hypergraph without--

00:46:37.820 --> 00:46:40.040
well, for Mantel's
theorem, we asked what

00:46:40.040 --> 00:46:41.885
happens without a triangle.

00:46:41.885 --> 00:46:45.560
For a 3-uniform, the
basic question you can ask

00:46:45.560 --> 00:46:47.940
is, what about
forbidding a tetrahedral?

00:46:53.590 --> 00:47:02.280
So suppose you do
have four vertices

00:47:02.280 --> 00:47:08.370
such that every triple inside
the four vertices is a niche.

00:47:08.370 --> 00:47:10.770
What's the maximum
number of edges

00:47:10.770 --> 00:47:17.600
you can have in an n-vertex,
3-uniform hypergraph.

00:47:17.600 --> 00:47:21.990
Already, it's not so easy to
come up with good examples.

00:47:21.990 --> 00:47:24.710
So Turán's theorem says
take a bipartite graph,

00:47:24.710 --> 00:47:26.700
complete bipartite graph.

00:47:26.700 --> 00:47:30.090
Well, here, it's not so easy
to come up with examples,

00:47:30.090 --> 00:47:31.890
but there are some examples.

00:47:31.890 --> 00:47:35.630
And in fact, Turán suggested
the following construction.

00:47:35.630 --> 00:47:41.790
Namely, you divide the set
of vertices, as before,

00:47:41.790 --> 00:47:46.610
to three roughly
equal-sized parts.

00:47:46.610 --> 00:47:50.960
And let me take all triples that
look like one of the following

00:47:50.960 --> 00:47:57.150
forms, either three vertices,
one in each vertex set,

00:47:57.150 --> 00:48:00.720
or a triple, looking
like that-- two

00:48:00.720 --> 00:48:03.580
vertex in one set,
one in the next set,

00:48:03.580 --> 00:48:06.990
or going cyclically, like that.

00:48:06.990 --> 00:48:11.870
So I include all triples,
one of these forms.

00:48:11.870 --> 00:48:15.990
And you should check
that this construction

00:48:15.990 --> 00:48:19.580
has no tetrahedron.

00:48:19.580 --> 00:48:21.340
If it had a
tetrahedron, you would

00:48:21.340 --> 00:48:24.910
have had at least two
vertices in one part, also

00:48:24.910 --> 00:48:28.566
then where the other
two vertices can be.

00:48:28.566 --> 00:48:32.640
If you check that,
it cannot happen.

00:48:32.640 --> 00:48:35.780
So then, how many
edges does it have?

00:48:35.780 --> 00:48:37.400
The exact number is
not so important.

00:48:37.400 --> 00:48:40.442
But what's important is
that the edge density--

00:48:40.442 --> 00:48:43.550
of all the possible
triples, the fraction

00:48:43.550 --> 00:48:47.840
of edges that are containing
this construction is 5/9.

00:48:50.700 --> 00:48:54.790
And it is conjectured
that this is optimal.

00:48:59.410 --> 00:49:02.500
However, we're quite far
from proving this number.

00:49:02.500 --> 00:49:09.920
So the best upper bound that
is currently available--

00:49:09.920 --> 00:49:13.640
and it's found quite recently
using this fairly new method

00:49:13.640 --> 00:49:16.730
in graph theory called
flag algebras, essentially

00:49:16.730 --> 00:49:20.840
a computerized way to try
to prove such inequalities.

00:49:20.840 --> 00:49:28.690
And the best upper bound
is something like 0.562.

00:49:28.690 --> 00:49:32.910
And there's a major open problem
to either prove or disprove

00:49:32.910 --> 00:49:36.780
that this construction
here is the optimal one.

00:49:36.780 --> 00:49:39.840
So you see, even though I
presented so many proofs

00:49:39.840 --> 00:49:42.210
of Mantel's theorem and
Turán's theorem, at this point,

00:49:42.210 --> 00:49:43.660
hopefully they should all be--

00:49:43.660 --> 00:49:46.200
they seem quite
simple in retrospect.

00:49:49.210 --> 00:49:50.100
It's deceptive.

00:49:50.100 --> 00:49:53.320
And even if I changed and tweak
the problem just a little bit,

00:49:53.320 --> 00:49:57.000
going to 3-uniform
hypergraph instead of graphs,

00:49:57.000 --> 00:49:59.670
we really have no
idea what's going on.

00:49:59.670 --> 00:50:00.170
Yes?

00:50:00.170 --> 00:50:00.690
Question?

00:50:00.690 --> 00:50:02.790
AUDIENCE: So
basically, how do you--

00:50:02.790 --> 00:50:07.250
why you say that this is really
bad compared to a two-number?

00:50:07.250 --> 00:50:09.355
It doesn't seem like
that big a difference.

00:50:09.355 --> 00:50:09.980
YUFEI ZHAO: OK.

00:50:09.980 --> 00:50:10.620
So great.

00:50:10.620 --> 00:50:14.380
So the question is, why do
I say it's a pretty big gap.

00:50:14.380 --> 00:50:19.070
So we know that there
has to be some proportion

00:50:19.070 --> 00:50:21.570
of the total number of triples.

00:50:21.570 --> 00:50:23.810
So, well, you have two numbers.

00:50:23.810 --> 00:50:28.290
And well, I mean, to me,
they seem pretty far apart.

00:50:28.290 --> 00:50:30.200
It's not some lower-order gap.

00:50:30.200 --> 00:50:31.600
So this is a first-order gap.

00:50:34.150 --> 00:50:35.145
Any more questions?

00:50:35.145 --> 00:50:36.770
But it's true that
later in the course,

00:50:36.770 --> 00:50:38.930
we'll see gaps that
are much bigger.

00:50:38.930 --> 00:50:42.820
We'll see gaps where there's
a polynomial on one side

00:50:42.820 --> 00:50:46.350
and a power of exponentials
on the other side.

00:50:46.350 --> 00:50:48.290
And there, I agree,
that's much worse.

00:50:48.290 --> 00:50:49.300
The gap is much bigger.

00:50:49.300 --> 00:50:50.810
Here, it's just two numbers.

00:50:50.810 --> 00:50:55.285
But in the worst case, there
can be two numbers anywhere.

00:50:55.285 --> 00:50:58.745
Any more questions?

00:50:58.745 --> 00:51:00.120
So throughout this
course, I will

00:51:00.120 --> 00:51:02.340
try to bring out
some open problems.

00:51:02.340 --> 00:51:03.850
And there are lots.

00:51:03.850 --> 00:51:05.970
So I will tell you
what we do understand.

00:51:05.970 --> 00:51:08.160
But most things, we
do not understand.

00:51:08.160 --> 00:51:11.850
And hopefully, some of
you will go out and try

00:51:11.850 --> 00:51:14.640
to understand them better so the
next time I teach the course,

00:51:14.640 --> 00:51:16.223
I could have something
new to present.

00:51:25.790 --> 00:51:28.880
So now that we've addressed
the question of what's

00:51:28.880 --> 00:51:30.920
the maximum number of
edges if you forbid

00:51:30.920 --> 00:51:35.090
a triangle or a clique, the
next natural thing to ask

00:51:35.090 --> 00:51:39.510
is, what about if you
forbid a general H?

00:51:39.510 --> 00:51:45.440
So give me a graph H. And what's
the maximum number of edges

00:51:45.440 --> 00:51:46.700
if you forbid that H?

00:51:56.430 --> 00:51:58.550
It will be helpful
to do some notation.

00:51:58.550 --> 00:52:02.750
So the extremal number,
which we'll denote by ex,

00:52:02.750 --> 00:52:06.920
and this is also called
the Turán number sometimes

00:52:06.920 --> 00:52:11.350
because of Turán's theorem.

00:52:11.350 --> 00:52:15.770
So I'll probably call it
the extremal number more

00:52:15.770 --> 00:52:18.240
frequently.

00:52:18.240 --> 00:52:21.560
So this number here is defined
to be the maximum number

00:52:21.560 --> 00:52:40.430
of edges in an n-vertex
graph containing no copy of H

00:52:40.430 --> 00:52:41.050
as a subgraph.

00:52:51.900 --> 00:52:55.090
I want to just clarify
a piece of notation.

00:52:55.090 --> 00:53:02.130
So when I say a subgraph,
so what do I mean?

00:53:02.130 --> 00:53:06.060
So there are several notions of
different kinds of subgraphs.

00:53:06.060 --> 00:53:09.720
And a couple that come
up somewhat frequently,

00:53:09.720 --> 00:53:11.280
one is subgraph.

00:53:11.280 --> 00:53:13.920
And then there's something
called induced subgraph.

00:53:21.200 --> 00:53:24.700
So it's probably easiest if
I just show you an example.

00:53:24.700 --> 00:53:30.170
So suppose my H
is the four cycle.

00:53:30.170 --> 00:53:34.910
So in the example of
H being a subgraph,

00:53:34.910 --> 00:53:38.900
suppose I have this graph here.

00:53:38.900 --> 00:53:49.770
So H is a subgraph of this graph
here in many different ways,

00:53:49.770 --> 00:53:53.316
but in particular, like that.

00:53:53.316 --> 00:53:56.070
But you see there are
some more edges that

00:53:56.070 --> 00:53:57.330
are among the vertices.

00:53:57.330 --> 00:53:57.960
But that's OK.

00:53:57.960 --> 00:54:02.070
So subgraph only requires you
to have a subset of vertices

00:54:02.070 --> 00:54:07.560
and a subset of edges,
whereas induced subgraphs--

00:54:07.560 --> 00:54:09.745
this is not an example
of induced subgraph.

00:54:09.745 --> 00:54:17.670
And so induced
subgraph means that you

00:54:17.670 --> 00:54:22.190
take this set of
vertices and you

00:54:22.190 --> 00:54:26.090
look at all the edges
in the big graph

00:54:26.090 --> 00:54:29.060
among your set of vertices.

00:54:29.060 --> 00:54:30.430
So that's an induced subgraph.

00:54:30.430 --> 00:54:35.720
So here, the four cycle is
an induced subgraph, but not

00:54:35.720 --> 00:54:38.730
induced subgraph over here.

00:54:38.730 --> 00:54:40.700
So I just want to make
that distinction clear.

00:54:40.700 --> 00:54:43.550
And for now, in
this chapter, we'll

00:54:43.550 --> 00:54:48.205
only talk about subgraphs--
so not induced, necessarily.

00:54:51.460 --> 00:54:52.000
All right.

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:54.710
So let's recap what happened
for Turán's theorem.

00:55:01.090 --> 00:55:09.900
So Turán's theorem told us that
the extremal number of these

00:55:09.900 --> 00:55:17.620
cliques, well, we know very
precisely to be the number

00:55:17.620 --> 00:55:21.110
of edges in the Turán graph.

00:55:21.110 --> 00:55:24.440
And in particular, we saw
from the last proof, but also,

00:55:24.440 --> 00:55:26.630
similarly, if you
just do a calculation,

00:55:26.630 --> 00:55:32.650
that it is at most this
quantity over here.

00:55:32.650 --> 00:55:36.860
And it's basically
that quantity.

00:55:36.860 --> 00:55:45.410
So the number of edges in this
Turán graph is asymptotically

00:55:45.410 --> 00:55:50.000
that quantity up to
a lower-order error;

00:55:50.000 --> 00:55:53.330
if you like n go to
infinity, r fixed.

00:55:56.050 --> 00:55:58.570
And the basic question
is, what about general H?

00:55:58.570 --> 00:56:05.580
And so if I give you some
arbitrary graph H, what can you

00:56:05.580 --> 00:56:08.430
tell me about the
maximum number of edges

00:56:08.430 --> 00:56:14.930
in the graph forbidding
this H as a subgraph?

00:56:14.930 --> 00:56:18.240
And it turns out, for most
H's, we have a pretty good

00:56:18.240 --> 00:56:20.370
understanding, and perhaps
quite surprisingly,

00:56:20.370 --> 00:56:21.870
because you can
imagine this problem

00:56:21.870 --> 00:56:24.030
looks like it might
get quite complicated.

00:56:24.030 --> 00:56:27.990
All the proofs that we've done
are very specific to cliques.

00:56:27.990 --> 00:56:31.590
But it turns out that we
already understand a lot.

00:56:31.590 --> 00:56:34.290
And the critical
parameter that governs

00:56:34.290 --> 00:56:39.640
how this quantity behaves is
the chromatic number of H.

00:56:39.640 --> 00:56:41.850
So if you call me the
chromatic number of H,

00:56:41.850 --> 00:56:44.520
I can already tell
you quite a lot.

00:56:44.520 --> 00:56:47.910
So just to remind you, the
chromatic number of a graph

00:56:47.910 --> 00:56:51.150
is the minimum number
of colors you need

00:56:51.150 --> 00:56:54.390
to properly color this graph.

00:56:54.390 --> 00:57:04.060
Chromatic number of
H, denoted chi of H,

00:57:04.060 --> 00:57:13.970
is the minimum number
of colors needed

00:57:13.970 --> 00:57:29.060
to color the vertices of H so
that no two adjacent vertices

00:57:29.060 --> 00:57:29.930
have the same color.

00:57:36.710 --> 00:57:44.730
So for instance, if I give you
a clique of r plus 1 vertices,

00:57:44.730 --> 00:57:46.920
so all the vertices must
receive different colors,

00:57:46.920 --> 00:57:49.090
because every pair of
vertices is adjacent--

00:57:49.090 --> 00:57:52.520
so the chromatic
number is r plus 1.

00:57:52.520 --> 00:58:00.991
The chromatic number of
the Turán graph is what?

00:58:05.290 --> 00:58:05.790
It's r.

00:58:05.790 --> 00:58:09.030
So the chromatic number
of the Turán graph is r.

00:58:09.030 --> 00:58:12.130
I can color each part in
this complete bipartite

00:58:12.130 --> 00:58:15.120
graph using a different color.

00:58:15.120 --> 00:58:17.230
And that's the best I can do.

00:58:21.470 --> 00:58:28.220
Now, if I have one graph being a
subgraph of another graph, what

00:58:28.220 --> 00:58:29.960
can you tell me about
the relationships

00:58:29.960 --> 00:58:31.460
between their chromatic numbers?

00:58:38.945 --> 00:58:47.227
So if H is a subgraph
of G, so what can

00:58:47.227 --> 00:58:48.810
you tell me about
relationship between

00:58:48.810 --> 00:58:49.830
their chromatic numbers?

00:58:52.752 --> 00:58:54.700
AUDIENCE: Chi of H is
less than the other chi.

00:58:54.700 --> 00:58:55.450
YUFEI ZHAO: So OK.

00:58:55.450 --> 00:59:00.790
You're telling me that the
chi of H is at most chi of G.

00:59:00.790 --> 00:59:03.050
And why is that?

00:59:03.050 --> 00:59:04.688
AUDIENCE: Because
if G can be colored

00:59:04.688 --> 00:59:10.503
with a certain number of colors,
then that also has [INAUDIBLE]..

00:59:10.503 --> 00:59:11.470
YUFEI ZHAO: Great.

00:59:11.470 --> 00:59:15.140
Whatever coloring you do for
G, you use the same coloring,

00:59:15.140 --> 00:59:17.760
and that's a proper
coloring for H as well.

00:59:17.760 --> 00:59:20.240
So the chromatic number
of H might be smaller,

00:59:20.240 --> 00:59:23.380
but certainly cannot be
bigger than that of G.

00:59:23.380 --> 00:59:34.580
So in particular, if you have a
graph H with chromatic number r

00:59:34.580 --> 00:59:44.400
plus 1, then this Turán
on graph is always H-free.

00:59:47.010 --> 00:59:50.310
So if H requires four
colors, it cannot be embedded

00:59:50.310 --> 00:59:54.260
into the complete multipartite
graph of three parts.

00:59:54.260 --> 00:59:59.380
So the Turán graph is also an
example of an H-free graph with

00:59:59.380 --> 01:00:01.160
lots of edges.

01:00:01.160 --> 01:00:07.380
And this tells us that the
extremal number of H is

01:00:07.380 --> 01:00:11.600
at least that of
this Turán number,

01:00:11.600 --> 01:00:18.316
where r is defined as the
chromatic number minus 1.

01:00:18.316 --> 01:00:23.128
So that's some
lower-bound construction.

01:00:23.128 --> 01:00:25.000
So as we saw
earlier, and we know

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:29.170
what the asymptotic is like
for the number of edges,

01:00:29.170 --> 01:00:31.769
this n goes to infinity.

01:00:31.769 --> 01:00:34.970
Namely, it's like that.

01:00:38.071 --> 01:00:41.340
And now the question is,
is this the right answer?

01:00:41.340 --> 01:00:43.410
Is it possible
that we completely

01:00:43.410 --> 01:00:48.680
missed some construction that
might produce a lot more edges?

01:00:48.680 --> 01:00:49.710
And it turns out--

01:00:49.710 --> 01:00:52.080
and I think this should
be somewhat surprising.

01:00:52.080 --> 01:00:55.230
Because so far, I feel like
I haven't told you anything

01:00:55.230 --> 01:00:58.950
all that surprising yet.

01:00:58.950 --> 01:01:01.590
This seems like a fairly
mysterious problem.

01:01:01.590 --> 01:01:06.210
But it turns out that this is
more or less the right answer.

01:01:06.210 --> 01:01:11.040
So you cannot do much
better than the Turán graph.

01:01:11.040 --> 01:01:20.090
And there's the theorem of
Erdos, Stone, and Simonovits

01:01:20.090 --> 01:01:36.240
rich that for every graph H--

01:01:36.240 --> 01:01:42.890
so if I fixed H,
then the limit as n

01:01:42.890 --> 01:01:49.340
goes to infinity of
the extremal number

01:01:49.340 --> 01:01:52.380
is a fraction of
total number of pairs.

01:01:52.380 --> 01:01:55.270
So here, this is
the edge density.

01:01:55.270 --> 01:02:04.590
So this quantity here is
equal to 1 minus chi of H.

01:02:04.590 --> 01:02:08.230
So 1 minus 1 over
chi of H minus 1.

01:02:08.230 --> 01:02:11.410
So the chromatic
number, in some sense,

01:02:11.410 --> 01:02:18.530
completely determines how big
the extremal number should be.

01:02:18.530 --> 01:02:22.010
And you see that so far
everything we've proved,

01:02:22.010 --> 01:02:25.140
Turán's theorem, Mantel's
theorem agree with this formula

01:02:25.140 --> 01:02:25.640
here.

01:02:25.640 --> 01:02:30.160
But if I give you some H,
maybe quite complicated,

01:02:30.160 --> 01:02:32.560
and those previous
proofs don't work,

01:02:32.560 --> 01:02:37.410
well, still you know the
first order asymptotics.

01:02:37.410 --> 01:02:38.660
But there's still more to say.

01:02:38.660 --> 01:02:41.030
But first, let me just
run through some examples

01:02:41.030 --> 01:02:42.370
for a sanity check.

01:02:42.370 --> 01:02:46.774
So if H is a triangle--

01:02:52.702 --> 01:02:59.340
so if H, the chromatic
number, and this limit--

01:02:59.340 --> 01:03:03.550
so if H is the triangle,
chromatic number is 3.

01:03:03.550 --> 01:03:06.230
So then this limit is 1/2.

01:03:06.230 --> 01:03:07.750
And that's indeed the case.

01:03:07.750 --> 01:03:10.240
So that's what we did
with Mantel's theorem.

01:03:10.240 --> 01:03:12.850
If H is a clique
of four vertices,

01:03:12.850 --> 01:03:16.510
then the chromatic number is 4.

01:03:16.510 --> 01:03:20.670
And the answer is 2/3.

01:03:20.670 --> 01:03:24.120
And also, that agrees
with Turán's theorem.

01:03:24.120 --> 01:03:25.630
It agrees with Turán's theorem.

01:03:25.630 --> 01:03:30.100
But I can give you some
fairly complicated-looking H.

01:03:30.100 --> 01:03:32.920
So for example, H might
be the Petersen graph.

01:03:39.680 --> 01:03:41.200
So every good
graph theory course

01:03:41.200 --> 01:03:45.710
should feature a Petersen
graph at least once, somewhere.

01:03:45.710 --> 01:03:48.660
So that's the Petersen graph.

01:03:48.660 --> 01:03:50.946
What's the chromatic number
of the Petersen graph?

01:03:50.946 --> 01:03:52.738
Actually, that's kind
of a tricky question.

01:03:52.738 --> 01:03:54.196
The last time I
taught this course,

01:03:54.196 --> 01:03:55.710
I even got the answer wrong.

01:03:55.710 --> 01:04:00.050
So it turns out you can
three-color the Petersen graph.

01:04:00.050 --> 01:04:03.390
So it's completely not
obvious how to do this.

01:04:03.390 --> 01:04:06.660
But there are only
so many vertices.

01:04:06.660 --> 01:04:09.240
If you stare at it long enough,
you can see what happens.

01:04:09.240 --> 01:04:12.220
But let me just show you a
three-coloring of the Petersen

01:04:12.220 --> 01:04:12.720
graph.

01:04:21.135 --> 01:04:26.640
Then the third
color is like that.

01:04:26.640 --> 01:04:30.880
So that's a three-coloring
of the Petersen graph.

01:04:30.880 --> 01:04:32.340
That's chromatic number 3.

01:04:32.340 --> 01:04:33.320
It's not 2.

01:04:33.320 --> 01:04:35.146
So why is it not 2?

01:04:35.146 --> 01:04:36.460
AUDIENCE: It's not bipartite.

01:04:36.460 --> 01:04:37.752
YUFEI ZHAO: It's not bipartite.

01:04:37.752 --> 01:04:40.770
It's a five cycle, which
cannot be two-colored.

01:04:40.770 --> 01:04:44.230
So then the limit is 1/2.

01:04:44.230 --> 01:04:47.410
And-- no.

01:04:47.410 --> 01:04:50.070
That's 3.

01:04:50.070 --> 01:04:51.030
Great.

01:04:51.030 --> 01:04:52.740
So the limit is 1/2.

01:04:52.740 --> 01:04:55.650
And here, I think that
we can apply this theorem

01:04:55.650 --> 01:04:58.350
of Erdos-Stone-Simonovits.

01:04:58.350 --> 01:05:01.420
And I think this should
be somewhat surprising.

01:05:01.420 --> 01:05:04.120
Because the Petersen graph
looks quite complicated.

01:05:04.120 --> 01:05:07.560
If you try to forbid
this graph in some big G,

01:05:07.560 --> 01:05:10.380
it seems like it's
kind of hard to do.

01:05:10.380 --> 01:05:12.380
But it turns out the
chromatic number completely

01:05:12.380 --> 01:05:18.120
governs the behavior of
the extremal numbers.

01:05:18.120 --> 01:05:23.510
But it turns out that's
not the entire story.

01:05:23.510 --> 01:05:26.280
Because while this is quite
a good theorem, and I said,

01:05:26.280 --> 01:05:28.700
it gives you the
first-order asymptotics,

01:05:28.700 --> 01:05:30.000
actually, that's a lie.

01:05:30.000 --> 01:05:34.010
It doesn't always give you
the first-order asymptotics.

01:05:34.010 --> 01:05:37.830
And when is
Erdos-Stone-Simonovits

01:05:37.830 --> 01:05:39.300
not effective?

01:05:39.300 --> 01:05:41.130
Or rather, it's
not the complete--

01:05:41.130 --> 01:05:43.490
it's not the final answer.

01:05:43.490 --> 01:05:48.280
Well, you can say, well,
what about this little o?

01:05:48.280 --> 01:05:52.610
So we're still trying to
understand, there's a limit.

01:05:52.610 --> 01:05:56.860
And you can understand
what is the--

01:05:56.860 --> 01:06:00.810
how quickly does it converge
to this number here?

01:06:00.810 --> 01:06:03.830
So that's certainly
a valid question.

01:06:03.830 --> 01:06:09.654
But more importantly, though,
if your graphic is bipartite,

01:06:09.654 --> 01:06:19.103
if chi of H equals
to 2, i.e. bipartite,

01:06:19.103 --> 01:06:22.190
then all this
theorem tells you is

01:06:22.190 --> 01:06:26.570
that the limit is equal
to 0, which somehow is not

01:06:26.570 --> 01:06:28.010
the most satisfying answer.

01:06:28.010 --> 01:06:30.590
You want to know the
first-order asymptotics.

01:06:30.590 --> 01:06:32.240
I mean, this still
tells you something.

01:06:32.240 --> 01:06:34.790
So the Erdos-Stone-Simonovits
theorem

01:06:34.790 --> 01:06:38.230
tells you that the
extremal number

01:06:38.230 --> 01:06:42.268
is little o of n squared.

01:06:42.268 --> 01:06:43.180
But of course, no.

01:06:43.180 --> 01:06:44.760
You are a curious mathematician.

01:06:44.760 --> 01:06:48.950
And you want to know, really,
what is the asymptotics?

01:06:48.950 --> 01:06:51.620
Is it like n to the 3/2?

01:06:51.620 --> 01:06:53.840
Is it like n to the 4/3?

01:06:53.840 --> 01:06:56.670
You know, is this
is not satisfying.

01:06:56.670 --> 01:07:01.810
And it turns out, from
most bipartite graphs H,

01:07:01.810 --> 01:07:04.040
it is a very difficult
problem that we still

01:07:04.040 --> 01:07:06.050
do not know the answer
to, even what is

01:07:06.050 --> 01:07:08.510
the order of the asymptotics.

01:07:08.510 --> 01:07:11.240
So the next few lectures,
what I want to do

01:07:11.240 --> 01:07:13.400
is to show you some
techniques that

01:07:13.400 --> 01:07:18.550
will allow you to
prove some upper bounds

01:07:18.550 --> 01:07:21.550
for this extremal
number in the case

01:07:21.550 --> 01:07:25.090
when H is bipartite that shows
you that the exponent can

01:07:25.090 --> 01:07:27.500
be less than 2.

01:07:27.500 --> 01:07:31.490
And I will also show
you some constructions

01:07:31.490 --> 01:07:34.940
that sometimes, but
in the very few cases,

01:07:34.940 --> 01:07:37.020
matches the upper bound.

01:07:37.020 --> 01:07:41.630
So there are very few examples
of graphs H for which we know

01:07:41.630 --> 01:07:43.860
the first-order asymptotics.

01:07:43.860 --> 01:07:47.450
And for most graph H, they
are major open problems

01:07:47.450 --> 01:07:48.465
in combinatorics.

01:07:48.465 --> 01:07:50.840
And there are some really old
ones for which any solution

01:07:50.840 --> 01:07:52.280
may be quite exciting.

01:07:56.580 --> 01:07:59.730
I will not show you a proof
of Erdos-Stone-Simonovits now.

01:07:59.730 --> 01:08:01.290
We will see that
later in the term,

01:08:01.290 --> 01:08:03.870
once we have developed
some more machinery.

01:08:03.870 --> 01:08:07.320
Although, later on in the
term, we'll see a proof using

01:08:07.320 --> 01:08:09.450
the so-called Szemerédi's
regularity lemma,

01:08:09.450 --> 01:08:12.720
which I've mentioned a few
times in the first lecture.

01:08:12.720 --> 01:08:16.270
Although, you don't actually
need such heavy machinery.

01:08:16.270 --> 01:08:19.500
So the original proofs
of Erdos and Stone,

01:08:19.500 --> 01:08:21.570
and also by Simonovits--

01:08:21.570 --> 01:08:25.290
so Erdos and Stone first
proved this result for H

01:08:25.290 --> 01:08:27.750
being a complete
multipartite graph.

01:08:27.750 --> 01:08:30.750
And Simonovits
observed that knowing

01:08:30.750 --> 01:08:32.760
H for a complete
multipartite graph

01:08:32.760 --> 01:08:35.109
actually implies this
result in general.

01:08:35.109 --> 01:08:38.430
So you will not find
a paper with all three

01:08:38.430 --> 01:08:41.170
of them being authors.

01:08:41.170 --> 01:08:45.328
But this is what the
theorem is called.

01:08:45.328 --> 01:08:47.870
So later on in the course, once
we've developed the machinery

01:08:47.870 --> 01:08:51.859
of graph regularity lemmas,
I will show you how you can

01:08:51.859 --> 01:08:56.992
deduce Erdos-Stone-Simonovits
from Turán's theorem.

01:08:56.992 --> 01:09:00.140
So somehow you use Turán's
theorem and bootstrap it

01:09:00.140 --> 01:09:04.380
to Erdos-Stone-Simonovits.

01:09:04.380 --> 01:09:06.810
So that should seem
somewhat magical.

01:09:06.810 --> 01:09:08.580
So on one hand,
you have cliques.

01:09:08.580 --> 01:09:11.399
On the other hand, you
have things that somehow

01:09:11.399 --> 01:09:12.750
don't have cliques in them.

01:09:12.750 --> 01:09:14.250
They don't really
look like cliques.

01:09:14.250 --> 01:09:16.460
But you can still
bootstrap one to the other.

01:09:16.460 --> 01:09:19.170
And so after we develop some
machinery, we'll do that.

01:09:19.170 --> 01:09:21.180
But there is a
combinatorial proof

01:09:21.180 --> 01:09:24.689
which doesn't use any
of this heavy machinery.

01:09:24.689 --> 01:09:27.750
I won't discuss it in lecture,
but you can look it up.

01:09:27.750 --> 01:09:29.200
And it's quite nice.

01:09:29.200 --> 01:09:30.930
It has some
combinatorial techniques

01:09:30.930 --> 01:09:33.004
and some double-counting
arguments.

01:09:37.840 --> 01:09:42.880
So going forward, I want to
show you some questions, mostly

01:09:42.880 --> 01:09:44.609
questions, but some
answers as well--

01:09:44.609 --> 01:09:49.640
so questions such as, what
is the extremal number of--

01:09:49.640 --> 01:09:53.920
well, so what are some of
the basic bipartite graphs?

01:09:53.920 --> 01:09:56.620
One of them is just a
complete bipartite graph.

01:09:59.140 --> 01:10:00.000
So this has a name.

01:10:00.000 --> 01:10:02.170
It's called the
Zarankiewicz problem.

01:10:02.170 --> 01:10:06.650
And for some values of s
and t, we know the answer.

01:10:06.650 --> 01:10:09.700
But for most values, we have
no idea what the answer is.

01:10:09.700 --> 01:10:16.510
For example for K4,4, we do
not know what is the correct

01:10:16.510 --> 01:10:19.472
exponent on the n.

01:10:19.472 --> 01:10:23.020
So even fairly small cases,
it is very much open.

01:10:23.020 --> 01:10:25.240
So this is all to show you
that these simple proofs

01:10:25.240 --> 01:10:29.425
that we did today, they are
perhaps too deceptively simple.

01:10:29.425 --> 01:10:32.587
Because even if you change
the question a little bit,

01:10:32.587 --> 01:10:33.670
we don't understand a lot.

01:10:36.540 --> 01:10:38.520
So questions like
these will occupy

01:10:38.520 --> 01:10:39.630
the next several lectures.

01:10:39.630 --> 01:10:41.390
And I'll also show you
some constructions.

01:10:41.390 --> 01:10:42.932
And there are some
constructions that

01:10:42.932 --> 01:10:45.540
use nice algebraic ideas and
some probabilistic ideas.

01:10:45.540 --> 01:10:49.730
So we'll see ideas coming
from many different sources.

01:10:49.730 --> 01:10:53.360
I want to close off by
just a cultural remark.

01:10:53.360 --> 01:10:57.110
So in this course,
especially the first half,

01:10:57.110 --> 01:11:00.530
we'll encounter a lot
of Hungarian names.

01:11:00.530 --> 01:11:02.600
So we already saw
a couple of them.

01:11:02.600 --> 01:11:05.000
And I just want to give
you a very quick tutorial

01:11:05.000 --> 01:11:08.490
on how to pronounce
Hungarian names, just

01:11:08.490 --> 01:11:10.370
for cultural purposes now.

01:11:10.370 --> 01:11:12.380
In the past, when
I took this CLASS

01:11:12.380 --> 01:11:14.000
there were no
Hungarian speakers.

01:11:14.000 --> 01:11:16.560
But I think we do have at
least one Hungarian speaker

01:11:16.560 --> 01:11:17.060
in the room.

01:11:17.060 --> 01:11:18.940
So I want you--

01:11:18.940 --> 01:11:21.020
but you are a native
Hungarian speaker.

01:11:21.020 --> 01:11:22.580
So you should tell us.

01:11:22.580 --> 01:11:26.288
So can you help us
pronounce these names?

01:11:26.288 --> 01:11:27.530
AUDIENCE: Erdos.

01:11:27.530 --> 01:11:29.150
YUFEI ZHAO: Erdos.

01:11:29.150 --> 01:11:30.900
And this one?

01:11:30.900 --> 01:11:33.720
AUDIENCE: That doesn't
seem like a Hungarian name.

01:11:33.720 --> 01:11:35.130
[LAUGHTER]

01:11:36.080 --> 01:11:40.790
YUFEI ZHAO: So this,
Hungarian, it's Simonovits.

01:11:40.790 --> 01:11:45.860
So I'll just tell you two
things about Hungarian names.

01:11:45.860 --> 01:11:47.637
One of them is that the S--

01:11:47.637 --> 01:11:48.470
AUDIENCE: It's /sh/.

01:11:48.470 --> 01:11:52.160
YUFEI ZHAO: --is
pronounced like /sh/.

01:11:52.160 --> 01:11:55.070
And another thing
that comes up is S-Z,

01:11:55.070 --> 01:11:56.870
which we saw in Szemerédi.

01:11:56.870 --> 01:11:58.560
So this is pronounced like /s/.

01:11:58.560 --> 01:12:01.275
Forget the Z.

01:12:01.275 --> 01:12:08.050
So Erdos, another thing about
Erdos that you should know

01:12:08.050 --> 01:12:09.190
is that--

01:12:09.190 --> 01:12:11.530
what is this accent?

01:12:11.530 --> 01:12:13.502
It is not a double dot.

01:12:13.502 --> 01:12:18.730
So in LaTeX you would
type it as slash H,

01:12:18.730 --> 01:12:24.460
and in particular,
not like that.

01:12:24.460 --> 01:12:31.320
So just a few cultural
remarks about names.

01:12:31.320 --> 01:12:31.820
Great.

01:12:31.820 --> 01:12:32.690
So we'll end today.

01:12:32.690 --> 01:12:34.910
And then next time,
we'll start looking

01:12:34.910 --> 01:12:40.260
at other extremal numbers
for more bipartite graphs.